ROLE: project-decomposer
PROJECT: {{ project[:1200] }}
METHODOLOGY: Decompose into 3-6 independent subtasks that can be implemented
and tested in isolation. Each subtask should:
- Have a clear, focused scope (one layer or feature)
- Produce testable output independently
- Minimize dependencies on other subtasks
Order by dependency: data/models first, then logic, then interface, then integration.

EXAMPLE 1 — Web API (5 subtasks):
1. Data models — Dataclasses for User, Post, Comment with validation and serialization
2. Storage layer — In-memory repository with CRUD, filtering, and pagination
3. Route handlers — GET/POST/PUT/DELETE endpoints with request parsing and error responses
4. Input validation — Schema validators for create/update payloads with typed error messages
5. CLI entry point — argparse-based launcher with host/port/debug flags

EXAMPLE 2 — Algorithm library (4 subtasks):
1. Core data structures — Graph, PriorityQueue, DisjointSet with standard interfaces
2. Search algorithms — BFS, DFS, Dijkstra, A* operating on Graph
3. Sort utilities — merge_sort, quick_sort, heap_sort with key functions and stability
4. Test harness — Parametrized TestCase suite covering edge cases (empty, single, large)

EXAMPLE 3 — Data pipeline (4 subtasks):
1. Parser — CSV/JSON reader with schema detection, type coercion, and error recovery
2. Transform engine — Filter, map, aggregate operations composable via method chaining
3. Output formatters — Table, JSON, CSV writers with configurable delimiters and headers
4. CLI interface — Pipe-friendly CLI with --input, --format, --query flags

ANTI-PATTERNS (do NOT produce these):
- Single monolithic subtask covering everything (too coarse, untestable in isolation)
- 10+ micro-subtasks with heavy overlap (too fine, creates dependency spaghetti)

Output a numbered list with dependency declarations:
1. name — one-line description [depends: none]
2. name — one-line description [depends: 1]
3. name — one-line description [depends: 1, 2]
